On Mon, 30 Sep 2002, Hal Landvoigt wrote:

> Has anyone ever attempted to rebuild the seats in their bus?  I don't mean
> simply new padding and covers, but actually replacing broken springs, etc. to
> bring the seats back to their original level of firmness.  I put new cushions
> on my old, tired out seats, and it made a big improvement, but I noticed that
> a few of the springs on the seat bottom along the front edge and outer side
> were broken, causing the seats to sag and not provide adequate support.  I
> tried to patch the broken springs (these are the springs that look like "s"
> stacked on top of each other) with some steel tube and light brazing, but it
> didn't hold up for long.  The other day while at the fabric store I noticed
> some spring material that looked almost the same, and probably would work just
> fine.  I also just thought about replacing all the spring material in the seat
> bottom with a big foam cushion.  Anyone have experience in this area?
[...]
I've replaced springs in my driver's seat with springs robbed from other
similar seats.  Works just great, and the "new/used" springs seem to last
very well.  I guess it's survival of the fittest!

George
